mong honeymooners. If you wish to sunbathe quietly while resting on the sand on the beach, here is the place to be. Because this beach is far from the city, there aren't many local tourists. 6. Lighthouse in pondicherry The Pondicherry Lighthouse is an excellent location where travellers may witness wonderful birds in various ways. Let us inform you that there are two lighthouses in this area, one ancient and one new. The historic lighthouse on this site is no longer open to the public. The French intended to construct a lighthouse to offer visitors a beautiful sea view. This was followed in March 1836 by the building of the old lighthouse under the supervision of A. Guerre. It was closed in 1979 after several years of operation. In the same year, another lighthouse was built, which is now one of Pondicherry's most popular tourist sites. This 157-foot-high lighthouse hosts cultural events, concerts, and commercial operations. 7. Gokilambal Thirukameswar Temple in pondicherry Gokilambal Thirukmeswara Temple is a lovely temple dedicated to Lord Shiva that is located in the little village of Villianur, 11 kilometres from Pondicherry. The French influence on this temple is obvious to visitors. A vehicle festival at the temple demonstrates the shrine's ties to French heritage. During this occasion, worshipers drag a 15-meter-high chariot through the city streets. 8. Sri Manakula Vinayagar Temple in pondicherry Sri Manakula Vinayagar Temple is a historic temple dedicated to Lord Ganesha in Pondicherry. The temple is supposed to have been built in the fifth century. On the 18th day of Brahmotsavam, many worshippers attend this temple. Vinayaka Chaturthi is an important event held with tremendous zeal at Sri Manakula Vinayagar Temple. According to legend, a Frenchman attempted to take the Ganesha idol from the temple, but it returned once the statue was gone. He became a follower of the Lord after being inspired by the statue's power. 9. Basilica of The Sacred Heart of Jesus in pondicherry This church, located 2.5 kilometres from the Pondicherry Bus Station on South Boulevard in the city, is one of the most important and religious destinations in Pondicherry. This church in Pondicherry is one of India's 21 basilicas. It was founded in 1908 by French missionaries and was later elevated to the basilica in 2011. In the church, holidays such as New Year's, Christmas, and Easter are celebrated magnificently. If you visit the city, you must stop by this gorgeous church. 10. French War Memorial in pondicherry The French War Memorial, located on Gobert Avenue, is an interesting tower created to honour the soldiers who died in World War I. Let us tell you that on July 14, this monument holds an annual memorial service, during which it is attractively decked. If visiting Pondicherry, you should also visit the French War Memorial. 11. Arikamedu in pondicherry Arikamedu is a remarkable historical monument and old Roman trading town located about a half-hour drive from the French colonial capital of Pondicherry. From the first century BC to the second century AD, the port city was held by the Romans, Cholas, and French as a notable nautical centre. Arikemedu's glass bead production facility is the most well-known in Puri. The initial excavations at Arikemedu began in the 1940s, and there has been continual excavation since then. 12. Raj Niwas in Pondicherry Raj Niwas, formerly called Palais du Sarkar, is a popular tourist destination in Pondicherry. The Raj Niwas is an eighteenth-century structure that presently serves as the house of the Lieutenant Governor of Pondicherry. The structure is not available to the public, yet it is a popular tourist site. The original court is also visible within a complex within this tower. The Raj Niwas' major draw is its monolithic pillars, which were transferred here from the Gingee Fort in 1751. Aside from that, several Gingee Fort pillars surround the Gandhi Mandapam on Promenade Beach. 13. Botanical Garden in 